segments.text: went on to Vietnam after a tour as a drill instructor at Quantico, Virginia, and suffered a bullet wound in the back of his head.
These things run deep, but the other guy got his girlfriend pregnant and he had to leave the Corps too, so that was two bad apples that left within a year or so of our arrival.
Now, if you got caught, and sometimes you wanted to get caught at pranks, this is no different.
Stealing your CO's footlocker or the fetal pig in the mess hall or anything else, it's okay because then we're all in it together.
Oh, and also then you get credit for the originality of the prank.
Is that part of it?
Sure, and we were, you know, we stole our, not only our CO, or his footlocker, but we stole him too, and
hid him out in the bushes and of course he beat us back in no time.
That was back when the university was trying to cut down on stealing foot lockers before the Texas game.
Where did you hide the foot locker when you stole it?
I don't remember.
I wasn't in on hiding it.
A couple of freshmen took it and they had a brother-in-law that lived in North Bryan, near as I remember, and it was in his garage.
They got it over there.
We only had four freshmen with vehicles, so it was, they were all our best friends.
It was hard to transport stuff around back then.
All right, and did you take it, did somebody take it out on the Kyle Field?
It made it out to Kyle Field.
What happened to the guys that actually carried it out there?
Did they get any punishment different from anybody else?

No, they escaped and they did it right at the right time when the TU band was coming off the field and they escaped and didn't get caught because it happened in Austin and nobody knew what to do with them.
So they jumped the fence and were gone.
trying to think of what else.
We also stole our CO's sink, too.
We figured, we had a couple guys in there that said, heck, let's don't stop with the footlocker.
They took him, let's do whatever we can to screw him up.
How did, was it taken off the wall?
Taken off the wall, yeah.
We had one guy that had pipe wrenches and everything.
We had a group, a subunit within our freshman class called the Aardvarks, and they would scrounge for stuff that we needed.
If our upperclassmen needed showerheads,

uh... the aardvarks would go steal shower heads and i know uh... rick perry and john sharp were both aardvarks in fact for a little while i think perry's nickname was the blue goose but uh... a guy named mike riesby that was in and out of our outfit about three or four times made it around final review with us i don't think he ever graduated but uh... he lives in baton rouge now constant discipline problem but uh... just one of those guys that is just part of the part of the outfit he uh...
He was in the aardvarks.

The best place to steal showerheads was Corps Staff, because they didn't have anybody to defend them, and they didn't have any freshmen to look after things, and they could get things fixed, so we pretty well, the upperclassmen wanted some requisition.
They never asked us where it came from, but steam tunnels were another choice method of transport.
When did you learn about steam tunnels?
How soon in the year?
Some, one of our, and I don't remember, one of our fish buddies
came in one Sunday night grinning and he'd heard about it from someone and
had gone exploring and these are the tunnels underneath all of the buildings on the campus.

And so got some, you know, a couple of us got some flashlights and we were scared and you go exploring around and we'd end up in different parts of the campus and sometime one night we heard voices and saw a light and we thought the campus cops were after us and then we got lost and then flashlight went out and that kind of cooled us on the steam tunneling for a while but
Steam tunnels were something that sort of passed on and people found out about but nobody advertises.
Did you ever hear of any injury, any unfortunate accident in a steam tunnel?
I've not.
I've never heard of a thing.
There's writing.
We found writing on some of the walls from
many years before us.
A lot of history down underneath the ground at A&M.
I don't even know if you can still get down in them.
I have no idea.
Oh, there's all kinds of security now.
Oh, I bet.
They've killed that fun.
How long was it before you and your buddies began to escape to go have a good time or something somewhere off campus?
Well, there were four
Four outfit buddies that had, four out of 56 had vehicles, and of course, numbers started to dwindle, but during the fall, you don't have, back then, didn't have much time to do anything.
We had, even though we're an Air Force outfit, we sometimes had Saturday morning drill and things like that, edge football games to go to.
There wasn't a lot of breaking out and escaping.
Those that could, that had steady girlfriends and just had to be away,

would find ways to get back to houston or to get to waco but you start you have your core trips and then one or two other weekends most of your expanding doesn't really start happen until your the spring of your freshman year and you've got a little bit more time and
you realize you're not going to die, and then you can get out and go do.
All right.
You had made good grades.
You were Midland Bulldog.
Lee Rebel, actually, but that's fine.
Oh, that new high school.
Yeah, the new high school.
All right, and how did the grades turn out, say, mid-semester?
Mid-semester we're good.
I was fine all the way through.

I had a focus on going to vet school and Carl Alexander, the boy from Louisiana, and myself had both posted, I think I had a 3.55 and he was 3.2 or 3.3, 3.3 I guess because we both were distinguished students.
That was a big deal in our outfit because they hadn't had a distinguished student in two years.
I remember they had a corps ceremony and Hector Gutierrez was the corps commander at that time.
He came by and pinned a little medals on us or whatever we did, but we thought it was a big deal and we were encouraged.
Was that at the first semester?
That was at the end of the first semester, so I guess that probably would have been early spring of the second semester, but midterm grades were fine.
I was
I don't recall, but I knew I was okay.
I wasn't worried.
You were taking probably 17, 18 hours?
I think I was taking 17.
Describe a typical class day routine for you that freshman year.
What time did you get up and what did you do?

get up whenever I never got up before the whistle jock and get up with the first whistle which I was probably quarter six six o'clock in the morning and blow whistles you shower shave get dressed fall out on the wall sophomores come inspect your uniforms ask you questions your detention on the wall for 15 to 20 minutes before you fall out for chow go to formation
You march to chow, you go in, you have your breakfast, get out, you have time to get back to your hole.
You have a mail detail going out.
Some freshmen's assigned mail detail for the day.
Somebody had laundry detail to pick up laundry bags.
and get your room ready for inspection, and then to head for class.
Classes would start, I always had an eight o'clock class, so I was on my way to class by 7.45, at the latest, 7.40, depending on where the building was.
That first fall had algebra, chemistry.
English.
English and history.
in a biology course, I guess.
Probably those five labs.
I never had any morning labs.
They seemed like they were always in the afternoon.
But going to class, seemed to have enough time to get from one class to another.
Didn't need a bicycle or anything.
Most of the classes, they were all in the central part of the campus, different.
I remember the, let's see, where was the history class?
Was it in the academic building?
Or was it?
Academic and Nagel.
I believe it was in Nagel Hall.
We were in Nagel.
Academic, I had an English class there.
And about what, do you remember the size of the classes?
Those classes were, for the most, the chemistry class was large.
There was probably 350 students in the chemistry, 300, 350 students in the chemistry class.
The algebra, English, and history classes were probably
Less than 25 students, 20 to 25 at the most.
And those were honors classes.
There was an honors colloquium, I think, probably on a monthly basis.
It was in the old physics building.
And this is where the... Where did, if you had an hour off in the morning, where did you take a break, or what did you do with a spare hour?
If you had time off, there were times, depending, you might go back to your home, go back to your rooms.
It was quiet.
There were times I'd go to the library.
There were times I'd go to the MSC, to Memorial Student Center.
I didn't, there wasn't really any other place to go that was fun to go.
When you went to the MSC, did you have a cup of coffee or a Coke?
Yeah, a lot of times you'd meet somebody, sit down, have a Coke or visit.
Yeah, there's almost always somebody.
And as a freshman there, we had one fish buddy that posted one grade point his first semester, Rudy Kretschmeyer.
I don't remember where he was, but he came to college with a custom pool cue.
Rudy made money at the MSC.
What he lost on tuition and fees and flunking out of A&M, he more than made up for hustling pool games.
And there was more than once I went over and watched that kid shoot pool.
I didn't know anything about it, but he was a master.
It would be interesting to know where he is now.
Oh, he's bound to have done well.
He was a hustler.
But the Corps wasn't for him, nor were the academics.
Did you all march into Chow at lunch, or did you go on your own?
I believe lunchtime we went on our own.
I don't believe we formed up.
You still, you blocked in at chow and you were pretty well at the mercy of whoever you sat with.
I'm pretty sure that's how it went.
I don't recall us having a noontime formation.
I think it was just morning and evenings we had our formations.
Then in the afternoons, if you didn't have a lab, if you had an unscheduled afternoon,
Typically, I was back in my hole, studying, getting things ready, if I'd had nothing else pressing.
If I had a project, if I needed time to go do something, I would go do it.
But there was no need for me to go anywhere else.
I had plenty of core activities.
There's always stuff to get ready.
There's always room stuff to fix up, always uniform, always studies to get ready.
If you have time and you need it, you can go take a nap if you can get away with it.
In your outfit, did upperclassmen bother if you were studying in the afternoon in your home?
Not much.
Some of them might come by and visit, but for the most part, they'd leave you alone.
And it was rare that you would ever have any outfit duties unless they had something needed to be done.
They wouldn't mess with you.
Normally, if you had things to do, that started around 5 o'clock in the evening, usually about an hour before chow.
What about intramurals?
Intramurals, that time period, that 4, 30, 5 o'clock,
we would have, that's when we had outfit football, things like that.
And do that till right before chow, get back, and then shower and change for chow.
And then if there were any pranks or any time at mealtime, it was at the evening meal.
Evening meals are where most of this stuff happened.
It seems like breakfast was pretty straightforward, but the evening meals you never knew.
And all of my fondest memories, more of them center around the mess hall than anything else, and some not so fond.
But the evening meal, the whole outfit was together.
It was before quizzes, but everybody, and I don't know what it's like now, but I have a feeling a lot of kids drift in and out, and there's a lot of different schedules.
Everybody came back home for the evening.
The family came home for the evening meal and nobody slept in and missed the evening meal.
Everybody showed up.
That was the one time everybody was together.
One of my not so fond memories when I was a senior, I was commanding officer of our outfit and we'd had problems.
We always lived near the band and so we always had friction, always problems.
I had three of my seniors that had basically no jobs in the outfit

managed Eastgate lounge a beer joint at Eastgate that was nothing but a template for disaster and from where they parked their cars it was a shortcut to walk right across the BQ drill field which would invoke the ire of the BQ's they would come out sometimes there were fights there were problems I found certain doors in the trigon to become very familiar because I was in vet school at the time and trying to run the outfit
I'd get back from vet school and have to go over the trigon and explain what happened the night before.
Anyway, one day evening, I was late for evening chow.
Executive officer took the troops to chow.
I got in just in time.
They're just starting to serve.
Sat down just in time to see a stud bucket, one of the iced tea pitchers, full, go sailing out of the middle of my outfit into the band.
And that was, I believe, a $2,300 food fight later that at least the good thing about your other outfits in the Corps, they would bond together with us.
And it was everybody against the band, and that's because they had more people.
Let's see, we mentioned nicknames.
I had a question about nicknames, but we've already mentioned that.
Oh, did the faculty have nicknames?

so I think that had vanished by your day there was one guy that some of the upperclassmen had I believe he taught statistics or something class I was never involved in last name was linger and they called him linger the finger I remember that I don't
I don't recall any now that's been in undergraduate days too far back, so I don't recall any other nicknames.

In the early days in the history department, there was one guy, extremely, extremely conservative in his politics, and he was called Screamin' Al, and he would cuss Roosevelt and the other communists in the Democratic Party.
And there were these characters.
And again, it was like the core nicknames.
These were kind of identifiers that, you know, he may be strange, but he's kind of okay.
Well, we had some in vet school, though.
We had Whispering Willie Banks, who taught

radiology and showed us an hour and a half of x-rays in a darkened amphitheater after lunch and talked in a quiet monotone and it was death and fell asleep in his class he'd fail you it was horrible so we would learn to answer for other students that were asleep the other was mad dog davis and some of those but those were vet school names
the first tests and the first grades, when did you begin to feel like, okay, I think I can do it?
I know when I got my first freshman chemistry quiz back, and I made a 94, and they posted the grades, computerized, it was early computer stuff, but they posted them
an old printout sheet just taped to the stone next to the wall, on the wall going into the doors.
And you walked up the steps, it was like going to Mecca, and everybody was crowding around looking at their grades.
And I saw a 94 and I thought, okay, I can do this.
And I remember
getting an A that same day on an algebra quiz that came back.
And so I knew that I wasn't going to flunk out the first week or two at A&M.
So I wasn't home free, but I knew I could do the work.
Did any of your buddies tease you or pat you on the back
that word circulating?

Well, a couple of us had done well, and we had probably five or six in the outfit that had done real well that first three or four weeks, and a couple of the upperclassmen called us goddamn grade point queers, and that old army was shot to hell.
This outfit will never be the same.
We've never had anybody, you know, do well in this outfit.
Kind of like an animal house, but...
No, I mean, for the most part, they, you know, the guys that didn't, you try to encourage them and the other guys, great.
There wasn't anybody that, we had some bright students, had a couple guys who were very bright that never, never did much.
They never amounted to much because they found other interests or things that took away from.
Who did you turn to for academic advice in your undergraduate years before you went to vet school?
We had an outfit advisor, but they, I never had any, any dealings.
Pretty well, you just did things on your own.
You could,

remember talking with a couple of upperclassmen that were in a different outfit that might be in the same same class that were okay that I could talk to and the problem is our sophomore class was so weak in our outfit they'd lost so many people none of them were in pre-vet and none of they were in AG courses and other things so there wasn't anybody in the outfit for me to talk to and that's one of the things that did as I stayed on in the outfit

we felt like we really needed to change and we got a little bit more involved with mentoring and tutoring with students and it was encouraged from the trigon and we had oh gee it was a doctor may have been land I can't remember from the college of agriculture that got to coming over when I was a junior I was in vet school at the time but he would come over and he would visit and counsel with a freshman that's probably some of the first but I was an academic scholastic sergeant and it
I think it helped.
Our attrition was not as bad.
Do you remember some of the first traditional events your freshman year?
Oh, sure.
Take your pick.
First Yale practice after you're at chow and somebody yells, tonight, and everybody jumps off and runs to Kyle Field to practice and do Yale practice, and then you

uh didn't realize the tradition of trying to steal each other's guidons and the fist fights that broke out and defending your guidon these are i thought wait these were supposed to be our core buddies about that time somebody hit uh mike reasonably in the back of the head and then all hell broke loose and uh
We took care of our own.
Court trip, freshman court trip.
Do you remember where you were?
I remember it well.
Fort Worth, Texas.
And I drove up there with Carl Alexander.

And this is, you know, it seems like nothing now, but for us to leave College Station and drive to Fort Worth and find the house where his date and my girlfriend and some others were staying, you know,
May not have been a country bumpkin, but wasn't used to driving in the big city either, so that was interesting.
We, of course, played TCU.
Had a fight at the TCU game.
We weren't involved with, but there were some TCU kids that got cuffed and hauled off.
They pulled a banner in front of the Aggie student section that said rotten to the core and had an apple core with a worm coming out of it.
Just can't let that stuff happen.
When y'all marched down the street that morning in Fort Worth, how did the spectators respond to the Aggies?
Well, you gotta remember, it was the fall of 68.
This is the height of the Vietnam War.
A lot of anti-war sentiment, and yet there wasn't any there.
It was, you know, God bless America, we love you guys, and it made you feel real special.
I have not yet had a single incident in 150 interviews
No, no, it was just, it was fantastic.
And what did you all do that you can describe, that you can talk about now on Saturday night?
Well, back up, that was Dallas.
We went to Fort Worth together, and that's where the girls were, but the actual court trip, and I remember it was in Dallas, and that was where we had our big...
party that night on Saturday night.
So it was SMU, not TCU?
It was SMU, that's right.
TCU fight was when we were sophomores, but the girls were over in Fort Worth.
Back to your question, it was... What did you all do that Saturday night?
That Saturday night we had a corps party.
They had a part of the convention center rented downtown in Dallas, had a live band, and
Of course, we were clueless.
We didn't have any idea, but it was a giant drunk.
And that's the way it was back then.
We got there a little late, and one of the girls had to go to the restroom, and she came out and said, there's two girls thrown up in there.
And I said, really?
And about that time somebody came out and he'd slipped in the vomit in the men's restroom, but it was just a big, loud, wild dance with lots of drinking.
What were people drinking?
Was it beer or whiskey or what?
Both.
Both?
Both.
And it's amazing because you've got a tremendous number of people who are underage, but it seemed to happen and it seemed to be okay and nobody got in any trouble.
So you came back home then on Sunday?
Came on Sunday, and that always...
There's a certain element of depression when we would, as freshmen, the closer you got to college station, the worst day in the world was coming back after Christmas holidays.
And we all got in, we all huddled in one freshman's room and one fished whole and all of a sudden we realized that there was at least seven or eight guys that weren't coming back.
At least, maybe more, but... Alright, now the semester ended before Christmas then?
No, the semester ended after Christmas, so we had, we still, we came back after Christmas, you still had finals to get ready for, so it wasn't, wasn't a good time.
It wasn't much fun, and on a court trip going back, everybody would, would straggle in.
We had some guys that straggled in at two or three in the morning, you know, way late to report in, but they took head count the next, next Monday morning,
check bruises on necks and bruises on noses, and I think pretty well everybody made it.
Nobody was in jail, so it was a successful court trip.
Your first silver taps, do you remember?
I do.
We gathered in the hall, and C.O.

and his roommate, Roger Matchin, George Schreiber was CO, Roger Matchin was his XO, explained to us through the addition of silver taps and being quiet, and tonight this is what's going to happen at 1015, and this is how you will do it.
And then the First Sergeant, Billy Hall, took over, and anyone caught talking, you know, is dead, you know, and this is a very solemn occasion.
And so we quietly streamed, soundless, from the Duncan area, and it was a very moving ceremony.
I'll never forget it.
Do you remember any silver taps for someone that you knew well?
Yes.
In 19, that same freshman year, I guess it was, was it in the fall?
It was probably in the early spring.
One of our fish buddies, Tommy Stein, died while we were running.
And just by God's grace, it was the Air Force 5BX exercise long run testing deal.
And we were out for an outfit run and doing all this stuff.
Tommy, who had been on the track team in Hondo, Texas, had a valve failure, and he died right there next to Duncan Dining Hall on the south side there.
And I remember our first sergeant, Bill Hall, giving him CPR.
So ours was a little bit different outfit, and this may have been one of the reasons we bonded so closely together, but our entire outfit went to the funeral in Hondo.
And we had a number of kids.
We had two or three from Hondo and DeHannis that were in, well, two or three in our outfit, and then
four or five in that area that were in the Corps.
And pretty moving deal.
We all wore uniforms and we were there at the Catholic Church and then the funeral there in Hondo.
Stayed up at Glenn Garrison's family's ranch north of Hondo, about 20 miles north.
And...
That Silver Taps for Tommy Stein was very moving.
And I know his younger brother, Wayne, has kids roughly the age of ours, and we've met playing baseball against Hondo.
You remember Coach Stein?
Yeah, these things go on.
You remember.
It's kind of like family.
And do you ever remember any mischief as a part of going to or from Silver Taps?
No, no.
That was sacrosanct.
I hope you've never had a report of any, but it is for real.
Those people that want to go to Silver Taps go because it's like going to church.
It's a worship service.
And for wherever you stand, it's still a very meaningful, solemn occasion.
And, yeah, it was never tolerated.
There was never any giggling, cutting up, grab ass, none of that.
This is an editor's note to be entered in at this point.

In the 1970s, when I was dean of faculties, a group of students came to me to seek my thoughts about whether or not Silver Tap should be held for an A&M student who died in a car wreck trying to make a getaway from a burglary in Brenham.
Was a student, and I told them that I had always understood
since I got here as a new faculty member in 1959, that Silver Taps was to be held for everyone who was a student here.
And I said, then I think you all need to decide, was this person a student?
For better, for worse, for richer, for poorer?
That's right.
And they did decide to go ahead and hold it.
I was thinking, who are we to be the judge for better or... Never called upon to do that.
The, let's see, bonfire that year, described by being a fish and helping to get bonfire going.
Probably, again, one of the greatest times, and I hope they have something to replace it for Kyle and his buds that come on, but ours was a stacking outfit, we would, I mean a loading outfit,
You had cutting outfits, you had outfits that would piss ant stuff out of the woods, and then you'd have outfits that would load onto the lowboys, and then they were taken to the bonfire area.
And there's a true science to this, and there's a way to do it, and a right way and a wrong way.
And we were schooled and taught exactly how to, and to this day, I've learned how to pick up heavy objects and how to school people and how to do it properly to keep from getting hurt.
And we'd lift the logs up and
The guys closest to the truck, we'd pitch them up, they'd switch sides, and then we'd slam them down, everybody's hands on top.
And we loaded all those trucks, and nobody ever got hurt.
We had wrestling matches.
When we had time off, it was people chewing tobacco, and we all wore red and white polka-dotted welder's caps.
Those were our outfit caps.
We were kind of an ag outfit, and we had...
There was a lot of, there were foot races and tug of wars and wrestling matches and a couple times we had freshmen against sophomores and they got pretty heated pretty quick, but it was all good fun.
We had one group, Spider D boys were a cutting outfit and they'd cut down a tree that had a bunch of honeybees in it and a bunch of wild honey.
And they left a couple people guarding the honey and
We went around and one of our boys, Fish Schwartz, said, hey guys, look at this.
And we stole half of their honey.
And just little things like that that make it all worthwhile.
Where was the cutting area, do you remember?
Don't recall.
Don't recall.
It was about, near as I can remember, it was probably about 15, 20 miles from the campus.
It wasn't real close.
And the bonfire was it on the drill field or at Duncan?
It was at Duncan.
Duncan.
And the bonfire was another one of these,
Oh tremendous bonding bonding bonding deal between that steel and the footlocker that really brought your your fish class together.
The bonfire belonged to the freshmen and it was we took a lot of pride in it I think the bonfire that year was a hundred and two foot tall.
About how long did y'all work on it?
My recollection I believe we worked on it
probably three straight days of loading, and then there were a couple of early weekends involved as well, but three straight days.
During that first year, were there any celebrities that came to the campus?
No.
Outside of
See, General Rutter died when I was, I guess, a sophomore.
You know, you had your town hall performers and that sort of thing.
I'm sure there were, I don't recall any,

or anything anything special we did have i can remember they weren't celebrities but we had as typically we had some kids from west point that were staying with one of the outfits and we had the privilege of taking them to the quad you know as soon as a upperclassman saw them and said you know don't mess around don't wait for the army kid you guys get in there you get them and so we took those west point guys to the quad
At the end of that freshman year, well, let's see, let's do Muster.
Did you go to Muster?
Not, not, where was I?
Yes, I did.
Went to Muster because we sat out on the lawn at the MSC.
That's where it was.
Went to Muster.
And, you know, things start happening pretty fast at the end of your
your fish year, there are positions coming up, there are awards, there are different things.
Those that are going to survive realize that they've made it.
How did you feel at final review that fish year?
I remember a senior in our outfit named Ricky Reynolds from Midland that had a big old scar face from a car wreck, but he
